{"title":"Hard Prompts Made Interpretable: Sparse Entropy Regularization for Prompt Tuning with RL","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"RL-based hard prompt tuning (e.g., RLPrompt) parameterizes Q-values via a frozen LM head multiplied by a small MLP, which effectively solves an extremely overdetermined weighted least-squares system over the vocabulary. This induces large approximation errors on low-probability tokens and a dense softmax policy that over-explores unlikely, unnatural tokens, yielding opaque “secret language” prompts.","method":"PIN mitigates the overdetermination and dense-policy issues by (1) filtering out ignorable tokens using the frozen policy LM’s own logits: for each prefix, only the top-k tokens by LM logit (k≈10k) are retained for Q estimation and action selection; and (2) replacing Shannon-entropy SQL with sparse Tsallis (q=2) entropy regularized Q-learning, which yields a sparse policy supported on a top-K_α set and uses a sparsemax-based target. Concretely, a filter operator F_I zeroes Q-values for ignorable tokens in both action selection and target computation, and the target value uses sparsemax over Q/α restricted to the supporting set. This combination reduces harmful constraints, curbs improbable-token exploration, and preserves probability mass on plausible tokens, producing more natural prompts."},{"problem":"Prompt tuning must work in black-box or non-differentiable reward settings and remain sample-efficient and interpretable across tasks (few-shot classification, unsupervised style transfer, textual inversion with CLIP). Existing gradient-based hard/soft prompt methods need backprop or embeddings, while RL baselines with softmax and ad-hoc filtering either over-explore or shrink the search space too aggressively.","method":"PIN keeps the efficient LM-head Q-parameterization but couples it with ignorable-token filtering and sparse Tsallis-regularized Q-learning, enabling reward-only optimization over a large yet pruned token space. It uses a frozen policy LM (e.g., OPT-125M/350M) to define the filter, a small MLP adaptor, a target network, and sparsemax targets; rewards come from task models including RoBERTa for few-shot text classification, learned style/CTC metrics for style transfer, and CLIP score for textual inversion. Empirically, PIN matches or improves over RLPrompt in accuracy (e.g., avg 82.8 vs 81.6 on few-shot), achieves higher J/GM on style transfer, learns higher CLIP scores with fewer interactions, and yields prompts rated more relevant and interpretable by GPT-4V than PEZ."}]}
